# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: superscalar-execution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] ILP must not be confused with concurrency.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] In ILP, there is a single specific thread of execution of a process.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] On the other hand, concurrency involves the assignment of multiple threads to a CPU's core in a strict alternation, or in true parallelism if there are enough CPU cores, ideally one core for each runnable thread.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] There are two approaches to instruction-level parallelism: hardware and software.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] ILP was implemented either as Hardware-level dynamic parallelism or software-level ILP static parallelism.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] With hardware-level parallelism, the processor decides which instructions to execute in parallel, at the time the code is already running, whereas software-level parallelism means the compiler plans, ahead of time, which instructions to execute in parallel.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Modern x86 processors use multiple techniques to achieve hardware-level parallelism, while the Itanium architecture made significant software-level parallelism possible, but also relied on it for its code to be efficient.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Operation 3 depends on the results of operations 1 and 2, so it cannot be calculated until both of them are completed.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] However, operations 1 and 2 do not depend on any other operation, so they can be calculated simultaneously.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] If we assume that each operation can be completed in one unit of time, then these three instructions can be completed in a total of two units of time, giving an ILP of 3/2.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] A goal of compiler and processor designers is to identify and take advantage of as much ILP as possible.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Ordinary programs are typically written under a sequential execution model where instructions execute one after the other and in the order specified by the programmer.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] ILP allows the compiler and the processor to overlap the execution of multiple instructions or even to change the order in which instructions are executed.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] How much ILP exists in programs is very application-specific.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] In certain fields, such as graphics and scientific computing, the amount can be very large.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] However, workloads such as cryptography may exhibit much less parallelism.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] ILP is exploited by both the compiler and hardware, but the compiler also provides inherent and implicit ILP in programs to hardware by compile-time optimizations.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Some optimization techniques for extracting available ILP in programs include instruction scheduling, register allocation/renaming, and memory-access optimization.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Dataflow architectures are another class of architectures where ILP is explicitly specified; for a recent example, see the TRIPS architecture.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Presently, a cache miss penalty to main memory costs several hundreds of CPU cycles.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] While in principle it is possible to use ILP to tolerate even such memory latencies, the associated resource and power dissipation costs are disproportionate.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Moreover, the complexity and often the latency of the underlying hardware structures results in reduced operating frequency, further reducing any benefits.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Hence, the aforementioned techniques prove inadequate to keep the CPU from stalling for the off-chip data.
[src:superscalar-execution/instruction-level-parallelism] Instead, the industry is heading towards exploiting higher levels of parallelism that can be exploited through techniques such as multiprocessing and multithreading.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In computer engineering, **out-of-order execution** (or more formally **dynamic execution**) is an instruction scheduling paradigm used in high-performance central processing units (CPUs) to make use of instruction cycles that would otherwise be wasted.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In this paradigm, a processor executes instructions in an order governed by the availability of input data and execution units, rather than by their original order in a program.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In doing so, the processor can avoid being idle while waiting for the preceding instruction to complete and can, in the meantime, process the next instructions that are able to run immediately and independently.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order execution is a restricted form of dataflow architecture, which was a major research area in computer architecture in the 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Arguably the first machine to use out-of-order execution is the CDC 6600 (1964), which used a scoreboard to resolve conflicts.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The 6600 however lacked WAW conflict handling, choosing instead to stall.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] This situation was termed a "First Order Conflict" by Thornton.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Whilst it had both RAW conflict resolution (termed "Second Order Conflict") and WAR conflict resolution (termed "Third Order Conflict") all of which is sufficient to declare it capable of full out-of-order execution, the 6600 did not have precise exception handling.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] An early and limited form of Branch prediction was possible as long as the branch was to locations on what was termed the "Instruction Stack" which was limited to within a depth of seven words from the Program Counter.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] About two years later, the IBM System/360 Model 91 (1966) introduced register renaming with Tomasulo's algorithm, which dissolves false dependencies (WAW and WAR), making full out-of-order execution possible.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the Model 91 the register renaming is implemented by a bypass termed *Common Data Bus* (CDB) and memory source operand buffers, leaving the physical architectural registers unused for many cycles as the oldest state of registers addressed by any unexecuted instruction is found on the CDB.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Another advantage the Model 91 has over the 6600 is the ability to execute instructions out-of-order in the same execution unit, not just between the units like the 6600.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] This is accomplished by reservation stations, from which instructions go to the execution unit when ready, as opposed to the FIFO queue of each execution unit of the 6600.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The Model 91 is also capable of reordering loads and stores to execute before the preceding loads and stores, unlike the 6600, which only has a limited ability to move loads past loads, and stores past stores, but not loads past stores and stores past loads.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Only the floating-point registers of the Model 91 are renamed, making it subject to the same WAW and WAR limitations as the CDC 6600 when running fixed-point calculations.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The 91 and 6600 both also suffer from imprecise exceptions, which needed to be solved before out-of-order execution could be applied generally and made practical outside supercomputers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] To have precise exceptions, the proper in-order state of the program's execution must be available upon an exception.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] By 1985 various approaches were developed as described by James E.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The CDC Cyber 205 was a precursor, as upon a virtual memory interrupt the entire state of the processor (including the information on the partially executed instructions) is saved into an *invisible exchange package*, so that it can resume at the same state of execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] However to make all exceptions precise, there has to be a way to cancel the effects of instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The CDC Cyber 990 (1984) implements precise interrupts by using a history buffer, which holds the old (overwritten) values of registers that are restored when an exception necessitates the reverting of instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Through simulation, Smith determined that adding a reorder buffer (or history buffer or equivalent) to the Cray-1S would reduce the performance of executing the first 14 Livermore loops (unvectorized) by only 3%.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Important academic research in this subject was led by Yale Patt with his HPSm simulator.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the 1980s many early RISC microprocessors, had out-of-order writeback to the registers, invariably resulting in imprecise exceptions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The Motorola 88100 was one of the few early microprocessors that did not suffer from imprecise exceptions despite out-of-order writes, although it did allow both precise and imprecise floating-point exceptions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Instructions started execution in order, but some (e.g. floating-point) took more cycles to complete execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] However, the single-cycle execution of the most basic instructions greatly reduced the scope of the problem compared to the CDC 6600.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Smith also researched how to make different execution units operate more independently of each other and of the memory, front-end, and branching.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] He implemented those ideas in the Astronautics ZS-1 (1988), featuring a decoupling of the integer/load/store pipeline from the floating-point pipeline, allowing inter-pipeline reordering.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The ZS-1 was also capable of executing loads ahead of preceding stores.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In his 1984 paper, he opined that enforcing the precise exceptions only on the integer/memory pipeline should be sufficient for many use cases, as it even permits virtual memory.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Each pipeline had an instruction buffer to decouple it from the instruction decoder, to prevent the stalling of the front end.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] To further decouple the memory access from execution, each of the two pipelines was associated with two addressable queues that effectively performed limited register renaming.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] A similar decoupled architecture had been used a bit earlier in the Culler 7.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The ZS-1's ISA, like IBM's subsequent POWER, aided the early execution of branches.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] With the POWER1 (1990), IBM returned to out-of-order execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] It was the first processor to combine register renaming (though again only floating-point registers) with precise exceptions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The reordering capability of even the floating-point instructions is still very limited; due to POWER1's inability to reorder floating-point arithmetic instructions (results became available in-order), their destination registers aren't renamed.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] POWER1 also doesn't have reservation stations needed for out-of-order use of the same execution unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The next year IBM's ES/9000 model 900 had register renaming added for the general-purpose registers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] It also has reservation stations with six entries for the dual integer unit (each cycle, from the six instructions up to two can be selected and then executed) and six entries for the FPU.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The reordering distance is up to 32 instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The A19 of Unisys' A-series of mainframes was also released in 1991 and was claimed to have out-of-order execution, and one analyst called the A19's technology three to five years ahead of the competition.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The first superscalar single-chip processors (Intel i960CA in 1989) used a simple scoreboarding scheduling like the CDC 6600 had a quarter of a century earlier.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In 1992–1996 a rapid advancement of techniques, enabled by increasing transistor counts, saw proliferation down to personal computers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The Motorola 88110 (1992) used a history buffer to revert instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Loads could be executed ahead of preceding stores.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] While stores and branches were waiting to start execution, subsequent instructions of other types could keep flowing through all the pipeline stages, including writeback.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The 12-entry capacity of the history buffer placed a limit on the reorder distance.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The PowerPC 601 (1993) was an evolution of the RISC Single Chip, itself a simplification of POWER1.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The 601 permitted branch and floating-point instructions to overtake the integer instructions already in the fetched instruction queue, the lowest four entries of which were scanned for dispatchability.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the case of a cache miss, loads and stores could be reordered.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Only the link and count registers could be renamed.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the fall of 1994 NexGen and IBM with Motorola brought the renaming of general-purpose registers to single-chip CPUs.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] NexGen's Nx586 was the first x86 processor capable of out-of-order execution and featured a reordering distance of up to 14 micro-operations.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The PowerPC 603 renamed both the general-purpose and FP registers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Each of the four non-branch execution units can have one instruction wait in front of it without blocking the instruction flow to the other units.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] A five-entry reorder buffer lets no more than four instructions overtake an unexecuted instruction.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Due to a store buffer, a load can access cache ahead of a preceding store.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] PowerPC 604 (1995) was the first single-chip processor with execution unit-level reordering, as three out of its six units each had a two-entry reservation station permitting the newer entry to execute before the older.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The reorder buffer capacity is 16 instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] A four-entry load queue and a six-entry store queue track the reordering of loads and stores upon cache misses.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Up to 64 instructions can be in a reordered state at a time.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Pentium Pro (1995) introduced a *unified reservation station*, which at the 20 micro-OP capacity permitted very flexible reordering, backed by a 40-entry reorder buffer.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Loads can be reordered ahead of both loads and stores.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The practically attainable per-cycle rate of execution rose further as full out-of-order execution was further adopted by SGI/MIPS (R10000) and HP PA-RISC (PA-8000) in 1996.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The same year Cyrix 6x86 and AMD K5 brought advanced reordering techniques into mainstream personal computers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Since DEC Alpha gained out-of-order execution in 1998 (Alpha 21264), the top-performing out-of-order processor cores have been unmatched by in-order cores other than HP/Intel Itanium 2 and IBM POWER6, though the latter had an out-of-order floating-point unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The other high-end in-order processors fell far behind, namely Sun's UltraSPARC III/IV, and IBM's mainframes which had lost the out-of-order execution capability for the second time, remaining in-order into the z10 generation.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Later big in-order processors were focused on multithreaded performance, but eventually the SPARC T series and Xeon Phi changed to out-of-order execution in 2011 and 2016 respectively.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Almost all processors for phones and other lower-end applications remained in-order until c.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] First, Qualcomm's Scorpion (reordering distance of 32) shipped in Snapdragon, and a bit later Arm's A9 succeeded A8.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] For low-end x86 personal computers in-order Bonnell microarchitecture in early Intel Atom processors were first challenged by AMD's Bobcat microarchitecture, and in 2013 were succeeded by an out-of-order Silvermont microarchitecture.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Because the complexity of out-of-order execution precludes achieving the lowest minimum power consumption, cost and size, in-order execution is still prevalent in microcontrollers and embedded systems, as well as in phone-class cores such as Arm's A55 and A510 in big.LITTLE configurations.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order execution is more sophisticated relative to the baseline of in-order execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In pipelined in-order execution processors, execution of instructions overlap in pipelined fashion with each requiring multiple clock cycles to complete.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The consequence is that results from a previous instruction will lag behind where they may be needed in the next.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In-order execution still has to keep track of these dependencies.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Its approach is however quite unsophisticated: stall, every time.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order uses much more sophisticated data tracking techniques, as described below.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] If input operands are available (in processor registers, for instance), the instruction is dispatched to the appropriate functional unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] If one or more operands are unavailable during the current clock cycle (generally because they must be fetched from memory), the processor stalls until they are available.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The instruction is executed by the appropriate functional unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The functional unit writes the results back to the register file.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Often, an in-order processor has a bit vector recording which registers will be written to by a pipeline.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] If any input operands have the corresponding bit set in this vector, the instruction stalls.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Essentially, the vector performs a greatly simplified role of protecting against register hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Thus out-of-order execution uses 2D matrices whereas in-order execution uses a 1D vector for hazard avoidance.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Instruction dispatch to an instruction queue (also called instruction buffer or reservation stations).
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The instruction waits in the queue until its input operands are available.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The instruction can leave the queue before older instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The instruction is issued to the appropriate functional unit and executed by that unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Only after all older instructions have their results written back to the register file, then this result is written back to the register file.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] This is called the graduation or retire stage.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The key concept of out-of-order processing is to allow the processor to avoid a class of stalls that occur when the data needed to perform an operation are unavailable.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the outline above, the processor avoids the stall that occurs in step 2 of the in-order processor when the instruction is not completely ready to be processed due to missing data.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The way the instructions are ordered in the original computer code is known as *program order*, in the processor they are handled in *data order*, the order in which the data becomes available in the processor's registers.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Fairly complex circuitry is needed to convert from one ordering to the other and maintain a logical ordering of the output.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The benefit of out-of-order processing grows as the instruction pipeline deepens and the speed difference between main memory (or cache memory) and the processor widens.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] On modern machines, the processor runs many times faster than the memory, so during the time an in-order processor spends waiting for data to arrive, it could have theoretically processed a large number of instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] One of the differences created by the new paradigm is the creation of queues that allow the dispatch step to be decoupled from the issue step and the graduation stage to be decoupled from the execute stage.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] An early name for the paradigm was *decoupled architecture*.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In the earlier *in-order* processors, these stages operated in a fairly lock-step, pipelined fashion.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The fetch and decode stages is separated from the execute stage in a pipelined processor by using a buffer.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The buffer's purpose is to partition the memory access and execute functions in a computer program and achieve high performance by exploiting the fine-grain parallelism between the two.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] In doing so, it effectively hides all memory latency from the processor's perspective.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] A larger buffer can, in theory, increase throughput.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] However, if the processor has a branch misprediction then the entire buffer may need to be flushed, wasting a lot of clock cycles and reducing the effectiveness.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Furthermore, larger buffers create more heat and use more die space.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] For this reason processor designers today favor a multi-threaded design approach.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Decoupled architectures are generally thought of as not useful for general-purpose computing as they do not handle control-intensive code well.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Control intensive code include such things as nested branches that occur frequently in operating system kernels.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Decoupled architectures play an important role in scheduling in very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The queue for results is necessary to resolve issues such as branch mispredictions and exceptions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The results queue allows programs to be restarted after an exception and for the instructions to be completed in program order.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The queue allows results to be discarded due to mispredictions on older branch instructions and exceptions taken on older instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] The ability to issue instructions past branches that have yet to be resolved is known as speculative execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Are the instructions dispatched to a centralized queue or to multiple distributed queues?
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] processors use queues that are distributed among the different functional units while other out-of-order processors use a centralized queue.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] Is there an actual results queue or are the results written directly into a register file?
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] For the latter, the queueing function is handled by register maps that hold the register renaming information for each instruction in flight.
[src:superscalar-execution/out-of-order-execution] while most later out-of-order processors use register maps.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] In a scoreboard, the data dependencies of every instruction are logged, tracked and strictly observed at all times.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Instructions are released only when the scoreboard determines that there are no conflicts with previously issued ("in flight") instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] If an instruction is stalled because it is unsafe to issue (or there are insufficient resources), the scoreboard monitors the flow of executing instructions until all dependencies have been resolved before the stalled instruction is issued.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] In essence: reads proceed on the absence of write hazards, and writes proceed in the absence of read hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Scoreboarding is essentially a hardware implementation of the same underlying algorithm seen in dataflow languages, creating a directed Acyclic Graph, where the same logic is applied in the programming language runtime.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Instructions are decoded in order and go through the following four stages.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] **Read operands**: After an instruction has been issued and correctly allocated to the required hardware module (named a Computation Unit in Thornton's book), the Unit waits until all operands become available.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] The read only proceeds when **write** dependencies (RAW) have been dropped from all other Units.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] To avoid Register File Port contention, a Priority Picker selects one Computational Unit (in the case where several Units are clear of hazards).
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] **Execution**: When all operands have been fetched, the Computation Unit starts its execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] After the result is ready, the scoreboard is notified.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] **Write Result**: In this stage the result is ready but has not yet been written to its destination register.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] The write may **not proceed** until the Unit is clear of all WAR hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] The only additional delays here are based on availability of register file ports: in the 6600 a Priority Picker was used to select one result per write port.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Once written the unit is marked as no longer busy, and all hazards and state is dropped.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Note that only in advanced (augmented, precise) scoreboards with "Shadow" capability will the Write Result phase be prevented (delayed).
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] The original 6600 did not have this capability.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] It is critical to note above that Reads only proceed in the **absence** of *write* hazards, and that writes proceed in the **absence** of *Read* hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] This is logical but contrary to expectations.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] In particular, note that Writes must wait to write after read in order to give other units the opportunity to read the **current** value in a register, before overwriting it with the new one.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Hence why writes must wait until the *absence* of WAR hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Thornton's book pre-dates modern computing terminology.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Stalling only occurred at the issue stage, when "First Order" conflicts were detected.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] Some other techniques like Tomasulo's algorithm additionally resolve WAW dependencies with register renaming.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] The original CDC 6600 likely did not have WAW hazard tracking simply because its designers had to deliver product, and then moved on to the 7600: stalling instead was the most expedient option.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] There is no *technical* reason why Register renaming should not be added to Scoreboards.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] An analysis of both algorithms was carried out by Luke Leighton and a transformation process outlined which shows equivalence between the Tomasulo algorithm and the 6600 Scoreboard algorithm.
[src:superscalar-execution/scoreboarding] WAW hazards resolution is indeed missing from the original algorithm: the 6600 would stall at the first occurrence of a Write Hazard.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] A **superscalar processor** (or **multiple-issue processor**) is a CPU that implements a form of parallelism called instruction-level parallelism within a single processor.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] It therefore allows more throughput (the number of instructions that can be executed in a unit of time which can even be less than 1) than would otherwise be possible at a given clock rate.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Each execution unit is not a separate processor (or a core if the processor is a multi-core processor), but an execution resource within a single CPU such as an arithmetic logic unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] While a superscalar CPU is typically also pipelined, superscalar and pipelining execution are considered different performance enhancement techniques.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The former (superscalar) executes multiple instructions in parallel by using multiple execution units, whereas the latter (pipeline) executes multiple instructions in the same execution unit in parallel by dividing the execution unit into different phases.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] In the "Simple superscalar pipeline" figure, fetching two instructions at the same time is superscaling, and fetching the next two before the first pair has been written back is pipelining.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Seymour Cray's CDC 6600 from 1964, while not capable of issuing multiple instructions per cycle, is often cited as an early influence to modern superscalar processors for its ability to execute instructions simultaneously through multiple functional units.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The 1967 IBM System/360 Model 91, was another early influence that introduced out-of-order execution, pioneering use of Tomasulo's algorithm.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The Intel i960CA (1989), the AMD 29000-series 29050 (1990), and the Motorola MC88110 (1991), microprocessors were the first commercial single-chip superscalar microprocessors.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Except for CPUs used in low-power applications, embedded systems, and battery-powered devices, essentially all general-purpose CPUs developed since about 1998 are superscalar.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The simplest processors are scalar processors.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Each instruction executed by a scalar processor typically manipulates one or two data items at a time.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] By contrast, each instruction executed by a vector processor operates simultaneously on many data items.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] An analogy is the difference between scalar and vector arithmetic.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] A superscalar processor is a mixture of the two.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Each instruction processes one data item, but there are multiple execution units within each CPU thus multiple instructions can be processing separate data items concurrently.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Superscalar CPU design emphasizes improving the instruction dispatcher accuracy and allowing it to keep the multiple execution units in use at all times.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] This has become increasingly important as the number of units has increased.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] While early superscalar CPUs would have two ALUs and a single FPU, a later design such as the PowerPC 970 includes four ALUs, two FPUs, and two SIMD units.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] If the dispatcher is ineffective at keeping all of these units fed with instructions, the performance of the system will be no better than that of a simpler, cheaper design.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] A superscalar processor usually sustains an execution rate in excess of one instruction per machine cycle.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] But merely processing multiple instructions concurrently does not make an architecture superscalar, since pipelined, multiprocessor or multi-core architectures also achieve that, but with different methods.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] In a superscalar CPU the dispatcher reads instructions from memory and decides which ones can be run in parallel, dispatching each to one of the several execution units contained inside a single CPU.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Therefore, a superscalar processor can be envisioned as having multiple parallel pipelines, each of which is processing instructions simultaneously from a single instruction thread.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Most modern superscalar CPUs also have logic to reorder the instructions to try to avoid pipeline stalls and increase parallel execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Existing binary executable programs have varying degrees of intrinsic parallelism.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] In some cases instructions are not dependent on each other and can be executed simultaneously.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] In other cases they are inter-dependent: one instruction impacts either resources or results of the other.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The instructions `a = b + c; d = e + f` can be run in parallel because none of the results depend on other calculations.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] However, the instructions `a = b + c; b = e + f` might not be runnable in parallel, depending on the order in which the instructions complete while they move through the units.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Although the instruction stream may contain no inter-instruction dependencies, a superscalar CPU must nonetheless check for that possibility, since there is no assurance otherwise and failure to detect a dependency would produce incorrect results.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] No matter how advanced the semiconductor process or how fast the switching speed, this places a practical limit on how many instructions can be simultaneously dispatched.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] While process advances will allow ever greater numbers of execution units (e.g.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] ALUs), the burden of checking instruction dependencies grows rapidly, as does the complexity of register renaming circuitry to mitigate some dependencies.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Collectively the power consumption, complexity and gate delay costs limit the achievable superscalar speedup.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] However even given infinitely fast dependency checking logic on an otherwise conventional superscalar CPU, if the instruction stream itself has many dependencies, this would also limit the possible speedup.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Thus the degree of intrinsic parallelism in the code stream forms a second limitation.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Collectively, these limits drive investigation into alternative architectural changes such as very long instruction word (VLIW), explicitly parallel instruction computing (EPIC), simultaneous multithreading (SMT), and multi-core computing.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] With VLIW, the burdensome task of dependency checking by hardware logic at run time is removed and delegated to the compiler.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Explicitly parallel instruction computing (EPIC) is like VLIW with extra cache prefetching instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Simultaneous multithreading (SMT) is a technique for improving the overall efficiency of superscalar processors.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] SMT permits multiple independent threads of execution to better utilize the resources provided by modern processor architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The fact that they are independent means that we know that the instruction of one thread can be executed out of order and/or in parallel with the instruction of a different one.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Also, one independent thread will not produce a pipeline bubble in the code stream of a different one, for example, due to a branch.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] A single processor is composed of finer-grained execution units such as the ALU, integer multiplier, integer shifter, FPU, etc.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] There may be multiple versions of each execution unit to enable the execution of many instructions in parallel.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] This differs from a multi-core processor that concurrently processes instructions from *multiple* threads, one thread per processing unit (called "core").
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] It also differs from a pipelined processor, where the multiple instructions can concurrently be in various stages of execution, assembly-line fashion.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] The various alternative techniques are not mutually exclusive—they can be (and frequently are) combined in a single processor.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Thus a multicore CPU is possible where each core is an independent processor containing multiple parallel pipelines, each pipeline being superscalar.
[src:superscalar-execution/superscalar-processor] Some processors also include vector capability.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The major innovations of Tomasulo's algorithm include register renaming in hardware, reservation stations for all execution units, and a common data bus (CDB) on which computed values broadcast to all reservation stations that may need them.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] These developments allow for improved parallel execution of instructions that would otherwise stall under the use of scoreboarding or other earlier algorithms.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Robert Tomasulo received the Eckert–Mauchly Award in 1997 for his work on the algorithm.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The Common Data Bus (CDB) connects reservation stations directly to functional units.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] According to Tomasulo it "preserves precedence while encouraging concurrency".
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Hazard Detection and control execution are distributed.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The reservation stations control when an instruction can execute, rather than a single dedicated hazard unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Instructions are issued sequentially so that the effects of a sequence of instructions, such as exceptions raised by these instructions, occur in the same order as they would on an in-order processor, regardless of the fact that they are being executed out-of-order (i.e. non-sequentially).
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Tomasulo's algorithm uses register renaming to correctly perform out-of-order execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] All general-purpose and reservation station registers hold either a real value or a placeholder value.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] If a real value is unavailable to a destination register during the issue stage, a placeholder value is initially used.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The placeholder value is a tag indicating which reservation station will produce the real value.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] When the unit finishes and broadcasts the result on the CDB, the placeholder will be replaced with the real value.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Each functional unit has a single reservation station.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Reservation stations hold information needed to execute a single instruction, including the operation and the operands.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The functional unit begins processing when it is free and when all source operands needed for an instruction are real.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Practically speaking, there may be exceptions for which not enough status information about an exception is available, in which case the processor may raise a special exception, called an **imprecise exception**.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Imprecise exceptions cannot occur in in-order implementations, as processor state is changed only in program order (see Classic RISC pipeline § Exceptions).
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Programs that experience **precise exceptions**, where the specific instruction that took the exception can be determined, can restart or re-execute at the point of the exception.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] However, those that experience imprecise exceptions generally cannot restart or re-execute, as the system cannot determine the specific instruction that took the exception.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The three stages listed below are the stages through which each instruction passes from the time it is issued to the time its execution is complete.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] In the issue stage, instructions are issued for execution if all operands and reservation stations are ready or else they are stalled.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Registers are renamed in this step, eliminating WAR and WAW hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] In the execute stage, the instruction operations are carried out.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Instructions are delayed in this step until all of their operands are available, eliminating RAW hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Program correctness is maintained through effective address calculation to prevent hazards through memory.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] In the write Result stage, ALU operations results are written back to registers and store operations are written back to memory.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The concepts of reservation stations, register renaming, and the common data bus in Tomasulo's algorithm presents significant advancements in the design of high-performance computers.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Reservation stations take on the responsibility of waiting for operands in the presence of data dependencies and other inconsistencies such as varying storage access time and circuit speeds, thus freeing up the functional units.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] This improvement overcomes long floating point delays and memory accesses.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] In particular the algorithm is more tolerant of cache misses.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Additionally, programmers are freed from implementing optimized code.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] This is a result of the common data bus and reservation station working together to preserve dependencies as well as encouraging concurrency.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] By tracking operands for instructions in the reservation stations and register renaming in hardware the algorithm minimizes read-after-write (RAW) and eliminates write-after-write (WAW) and Write-after-Read (WAR) computer architecture hazards.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] This improves performance by reducing wasted time that would otherwise be required for stalls.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] An equally important improvement in the algorithm is the design is not limited to a specific pipeline structure.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] This improvement allows the algorithm to be more widely adopted by multiple-issue processors.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Additionally, the algorithm is easily extended to enable branch speculation.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Tomasulo's algorithm was implemented in the System/360 Model 91 architecture.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Outside of IBM, it went unused for several years.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Dynamic scheduling and branch speculation from the algorithm enables improved performance as processors issued more and more instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Proliferation of mass-market software meant that programmers would not want to compile for a specific pipeline structure.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] The algorithm can function with any pipeline architecture and thus software requires few architecture-specific modifications.
[src:superscalar-execution/tomasulo-s-algorithm] Many modern processors implement dynamic scheduling schemes that are variants of Tomasulo's original algorithm, including popular Intel x86-64 chips.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW architectures contrast with superscalar architectures, the predominant approach for exploiting ILP, where hardware dynamically discovers and schedules parallel execution at runtime.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW's primary motivation is achieving higher performance without the hardware complexity of superscalar designs.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The circuitry needed to repeatedly analyze instruction streams and schedule parallel execution at runtime increases chip area, cost, and power consumption while potentially reducing clock speeds.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The name VLIW derives from the instruction format found in almost all implementations, where the compiler bundles operations intended to execute simultaneously into a single, wide instruction word dispatched to execution units as one unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These words can be extremely wide—implementations have used instruction words of 1 kilobit or more.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] But this is only a side effect of the natural way to implement a VLIW.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The distinguishing feature of a VLIW is that the exact execution order and parallelism are discovered and specified in advance.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW shifts the burden of identifying parallelism from hardware to the compiler.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This increases compiler complexity substantially, as it must schedule instructions while ensuring correctness, resolving resource conflicts (for execution units, registers, and memory ports), and exploiting the greater parallelism that simpler VLIW hardware exposes.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The concept of VLIW architecture, and the term *VLIW*, were invented by Josh Fisher in his research group at Yale University in the early 1980s.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] His original development of trace scheduling as a compiling method for VLIW was developed when he was a graduate student at New York University.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Before VLIW, the notion of prescheduling execution units and instruction-level parallelism in software was well established in the practice of developing horizontal microcode.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Fisher's innovations involved developing a compiler that could target horizontal microcode from programs written in an ordinary programming language.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] He realized that to get good performance and target a wide-issue machine, it would be necessary to find parallelism beyond that generally within a basic block.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] He also developed region scheduling methods to identify parallelism beyond basic blocks.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Trace scheduling is such a method, and involves scheduling the most likely path of basic blocks first, inserting compensating code to deal with speculative motions, scheduling the second most likely trace, and so on, until the schedule is complete.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Fisher's second innovation was the notion that the target CPU architecture should be designed to be a reasonable target for a compiler; that the compiler and the architecture for a VLIW processor must be codesigned.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Fisher developed a set of principles characterizing a proper VLIW design, such as self-draining pipelines, wide multi-port register files, and memory architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These principles made it easier for compilers to emit fast code.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The first VLIW compiler was described in a Ph.D. thesis by John Ellis, supervised by Fisher.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The compiler was named Bulldog, after Yale's mascot.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Fisher left Yale in 1984 to found a startup company, Multiflow, along with cofounders John O'Donnell and John Ruttenberg.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Multiflow produced the TRACE series of VLIW minisupercomputers, shipping their first machines in 1987.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Multiflow's VLIW could issue 28 operations in parallel per instruction.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Multiflow was too early to catch the following wave, when chip architectures began to allow multiple-issue CPUs.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The major semiconductor companies recognized the value of Multiflow technology in this context, so the compiler and architecture were subsequently licensed to most of these firms.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] A processor that executes every instruction one after the other (i.e., a non-pipelined scalar architecture) may use processor resources inefficiently, yielding potential poor performance.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The performance can be improved by executing different substeps of sequential instructions simultaneously (termed *pipelining*), or even executing multiple instructions entirely simultaneously as in superscalar architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Further improvement can be achieved by executing instructions in an order different from that in which they occur in a program, termed out-of-order execution.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These three methods all raise hardware complexity.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Before executing any operations in parallel, the processor must verify that the instructions have no interdependencies.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] For example, if a first instruction's result is used as a second instruction's input, then they cannot execute at the same time and the second instruction cannot execute before the first.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Modern out-of-order processors have increased the hardware resources which schedule instructions and determine interdependencies.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In contrast, VLIW executes operations in parallel, based on a fixed schedule, determined when programs are compiled.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Since determining the order of execution of operations (including which operations can execute simultaneously) is handled by the compiler, the processor does not need the scheduling hardware that the three methods described above require.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Thus, VLIW CPUs offer more computing with less hardware complexity (but greater compiler complexity) than do most superscalar CPUs.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This is also complementary to the idea that as many computations as possible should be done before the program is executed, at compile time.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In superscalar designs, the number of execution units is invisible to the instruction set.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Each instruction encodes one operation only.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] For most superscalar designs, the instruction width is 32 bits or fewer.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In contrast, one VLIW instruction encodes multiple operations, at least one operation for each execution unit of a device.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] For example, if a VLIW device has five execution units, then a VLIW instruction for the device has five operation fields, each field specifying what operation should be done on that corresponding execution unit.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] To accommodate these operation fields, VLIW instructions are usually at least 64 bits wide, and far wider on some architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] For example, the following is an instruction for the Super Harvard Architecture Single-Chip Computer (SHARC).
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In one cycle, it does a floating-point multiply, a floating-point add, and two autoincrement loads.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Since the earliest days of computer architecture, some CPUs have added several arithmetic logic units (ALUs) to run in parallel.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Superscalar CPUs use hardware to decide which operations can run in parallel at runtime, while VLIW CPUs use software (the compiler) to decide which operations can run in parallel in advance.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Because the complexity of instruction scheduling is moved into the compiler, complexity of hardware can be reduced substantially.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] A similar problem occurs when the result of a parallelizable instruction is used as input for a branch.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Most modern CPUs *guess* which branch will be taken even before the calculation is complete, so that they can load the instructions for the branch, or (in some architectures) even start to compute them speculatively.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] If the CPU guesses wrong, all of these instructions and their context need to be *flushed* and the correct ones loaded, which takes time.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This has led to increasingly complex instruction-dispatch logic that attempts to guess correctly, and the simplicity of the original reduced instruction set computing (RISC) designs has been eroded.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW lacks this logic, and thus lacks its energy use, possible design defects, and other negative aspects.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In a VLIW, the compiler uses heuristics or profile information to guess the direction of a branch.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This allows it to move and preschedule operations speculatively before the branch is taken, favoring the most likely path it expects through the branch.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] If the branch takes an unexpected way, the compiler has already generated compensating code to discard speculative results to preserve program semantics.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Vector processor cores (designed for large one-dimensional arrays of data called *vectors*) can be combined with the VLIW architecture such as in the Fujitsu FR-V microprocessor, further increasing throughput and speed.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Cydrome was a company producing VLIW numeric processors using emitter-coupled logic (ECL) integrated circuits in the same timeframe (late 1980s).
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This company, like Multiflow, failed after a few years.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] One of the licensees of the Multiflow technology is Hewlett-Packard, which Josh Fisher joined after Multiflow's demise.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Bob Rau, founder of Cydrome, also joined HP after Cydrome failed.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These two would lead computer architecture research at Hewlett-Packard during the 1990s.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Along with the above systems, during the same time (1989–1990), Intel implemented VLIW in the Intel i860, their first 64-bit microprocessor, and the first processor to implement VLIW on one chip.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The i860's VLIW mode was used extensively in embedded digital signal processor (DSP) applications since the application execution and datasets were simple, well ordered and predictable, allowing designers to fully exploit the parallel execution advantages enabled by VLIW.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In VLIW mode, the i860 could maintain floating-point performance in the range of 20-40 double-precision MFLOPS; a very high value for its time and for a processor running at 25-50Mhz.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In the 1990s, Hewlett-Packard researched this problem as a side effect of ongoing work on their PA-RISC processor family.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] They found that the CPU could be greatly simplified by removing the complex dispatch logic from the CPU and placing it in the compiler.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Compilers of the day were far more complex than those of the 1980s, so the added complexity in the compiler was considered to be a small cost.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW CPUs are usually made of multiple RISC-like execution units that operate independently.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Later VLIWs usually have four to eight main execution units.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Compilers generate initial instruction sequences for the VLIW CPU in roughly the same manner as for traditional CPUs, generating a sequence of RISC-like instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The compiler analyzes this code for dependence relationships and resource requirements.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] It then schedules the instructions according to those constraints.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In this process, independent instructions can be scheduled in parallel.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Because VLIWs typically represent instructions scheduled in parallel with a longer instruction word that incorporates the individual instructions, this results in a much longer opcode (termed *very long*) to specify what executes on a given cycle.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The Texas Instruments TMS320 DSP line has evolved, in its C6000 family, to look more like a VLIW, in contrast to the earlier C5000 family.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] One or more Qualcomm Hexagons were used in cell phone designs.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These VLIW CPUs are used mainly as embedded media processors for consumer electronic devices.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW features have also been added to configurable processor cores for system-on-a-chip (SoC) designs.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] For example, Tensilica's Xtensa LX2 processor incorporates a technology named Flexible Length Instruction eXtensions (FLIX) that allows multi-operation instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The Xtensa C/C++ compiler can freely intermix 32- or 64-bit FLIX instructions with the Xtensa processor's one-operation RISC instructions, which are 16 or 24 bits wide.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] By packing multiple operations into a wide 32- or 64-bit instruction word and allowing these multi-operation instructions to intermix with shorter RISC instructions, FLIX allows SoC designers to realize VLIW's performance advantages while eliminating the code bloat of early VLIW architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The Infineon Carmel DSP is another VLIW processor core intended for SoC.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] It uses a similar code density improvement method called *configurable long instruction word* (CLIW).
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Outside embedded processing markets, Intel's Itanium IA-64 explicitly parallel instruction computing (EPIC) and Elbrus 2000 appear as the only examples of a widely used VLIW CPU architectures.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] However, EPIC architecture is sometimes distinguished from a pure VLIW architecture, since EPIC advocates full instruction predication, rotating register files, and a very long instruction word that can encode non-parallel instruction groups.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIWs also gained significant consumer penetration in the graphics processing unit (GPU) market, though both Nvidia and AMD have since moved to RISC architectures to improve performance on non-graphics workloads.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] ATI Technologies' (ATI) and Advanced Micro Devices' (AMD) TeraScale microarchitecture for graphics processing units (GPUs) is a VLIW microarchitecture.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] In December 2015, the first shipment of PCs based on VLIW CPU Elbrus-4s was made in Russia.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The Neo by REX Computing is a processor consisting of a 2D mesh of VLIW cores aimed at power efficiency.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] The Elbrus 2000 (Russian: Эльбрус 2000) and its successors are Russian 512-bit wide VLIW microprocessors developed by Moscow Center of SPARC Technologies (MCST) and fabricated by TSMC.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] When silicon technology allowed for wider implementations (with more execution units) to be built, the compiled programs for the earlier generation would not run on the wider implementations, as the encoding of binary instructions depended on the number of execution units of the machine.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Transmeta addressed this issue by including a binary-to-binary software compiler layer (termed *code morphing*) in their Crusoe implementation of the x86 architecture.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This mechanism was advertised to basically recompile, optimize, and translate x86 opcodes at runtime into the CPU's internal machine code.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Thus, the Transmeta chip is *internally* a VLIW processor, effectively decoupled from the x86 CISC instruction set that it executes.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Intel's Itanium architecture (among others) solved the backward-compatibility problem with a more general mechanism.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Within each of the multiple-opcode instructions, a bit field is allocated to denote dependency on the prior VLIW instruction within the program instruction stream.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] These bits are set at compile time, thus relieving the hardware from calculating this dependency information.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Having this dependency information encoded in the instruction stream allows wider implementations to issue multiple non-dependent VLIW instructions in parallel per cycle, while narrower implementations would issue a smaller number of VLIW instructions per cycle.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Another perceived deficiency of VLIW designs is the code bloat that occurs when one or more execution unit(s) have no useful work to do and thus must execute *No Operation* NOP instructions.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] This occurs when there are dependencies in the code and the instruction pipelines must be allowed to drain before later operations can proceed.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] Since the number of transistors on a chip has grown, the perceived disadvantages of the VLIW have diminished in importance.
[src:superscalar-execution/very-long-instruction-word] VLIW architectures are growing in popularity, especially in the embedded system market, where it is possible to customize a processor for an application in a system-on-a-chip.
